segments.text: In the early 30s, you couldn't find anybody in Texas except a Democrat.
My grandfather, boy, he'd read the paper every day and anything that was counted as a Democratic party.
Of course, you couldn't get elected in the South, but particularly Texas.
And so they may have been Republican philosophy somewhere, but...
But as you just mentioned, very few people knew anything about Republicans.
You had to go back to Hoover.
And everybody said he was responsible for depression, which, of course, he wasn't.
But he happened to be the guy that gets blamed for it.
So no, to answer your question, I guess a political philosophy never did enter my mind.
as I was growing up.
And I don't know anybody that I associated with very strongly because nobody ever talked about anything except Democrats.
Now, over the years, would you consider yourself a conservative, moderate, or a liberal?
And what parties did you support over the years?
I'm ashamed to say this, but until I retired, I never did vote.
And the reason why it makes it very difficult for the military, because you're gone, you've got to send in an absentee vote.
And up until a few years ago, you had to pay your poll tax.
And I wanted to go pay poll tax and back to the, which I was against poll tax.
We know what the poll tax was for.
It keeps the blacks away.
And poor white kind of eliminated a whole element of society.
But to answer your question, I think I've always been more on the conservative side in political philosophy.
Of course, if I had voted back in those days, I would have voted for Roosevelt, no question in my mind.
What about more recent America?
I guess I tend to be more conservative.
I vote Republican now.
I voted in every election since I retired, local and then
I'm active now in the community.
And are you a member of the Republican Party?
Yeah.
But back in those days in the military, once again, there are two reasons for that.
That's pretty typical.
A lot of officers didn't vote.
Well, one reason is that nobody has ever appealed to the military to... We've never been involved with politics.
And I'm horrified when somebody tries to tie us to politics.
For example, they wanted to fire the chairman of the Joint Chiefs, see, because he supported a program of Carter.

Well, that would be a hell of a note if we ever got to a point that every time you change presidents, you purge your military and get rid of all the leaders and bring in somebody else, you'll end up being like a banana republic.
And that was a very dangerous thing.
But fortunately, Reagan, an advisor, said, absolutely not.
He will continue and fulfill his term.
And he's not going to be replaced because he went along with reluctantly.
And he's an Air Force officer.
Reluctantly was the B-1.
You can't have military to lead a revolt against their, I don't mean a physical revolt,
media revolt against the president if you disagree with the decision he's made.
All you got to do is resign if that's the way you feel.
And most of them, and I subscribe to this, they can do more good for all of the principles that they stand for to stay rather than to run.
That would be a difficult situation too if every time the president made a decision that the leaders
and the military disliked, they would all resign.
Because a professional soldier to me is the nation.
Just like West Point, duty, honor, and country.
And it's not political persuasion.
And so from that standpoint, I don't think the military should get involved in politics.
Now voting, of course, is a different thing.
But even then, I don't think we should get out a letter to each other and say, now let's all get together.
and vote Republican or Democrat or something like that.
And you work with your troops, you know, you tell them.
Yeah, absolutely.
So the military ought to stay completely away from politics, even if it means that you're not taking advantage of your vote.
The other thing is, I don't think that somebody stationed in Germany, which I spent some time there in other parts of the world,
should have an influence on a local election.
They're not there.
They don't know the people.
So they'd have to vote either.
Somebody said, hey, would you please submit your application and vote for so-and-so?
And they don't even know the issues.
That's right.
You don't even know the person.
It'd be better if you just stayed out and let the people who are not.
We have a situation here in Austin that's kind of, well, we who live here, it's kind of touchy.
The university students, they vote on a local issue.
And some of them, for example, now it's coming up here in the fall, the nuclear plant down in Bayport.
Now you have these young people that come in from all over the state, and they vote here in a local election.
They graduate, and they're gone, or maybe not even.
They've elected members of the council, for example,
Most of them are liberal, idealistic, as they should be.
So they vote for the liberals.
So as a result, the more conservative are defeated.
Well, it's good for the liberals to be on there, but I don't think it's good for the conservatives.
Of course, it isn't the university students' fault.
This is the other side of the coin.
If the eligible voters would get out and vote,
That wouldn't be such an influence.
But they don't do that.
So anyway, going back to the military, it's the same.
We should not be political at all.
Now, when you were in the Corps, tell me about your unit.
Well, at that time, we had a regiment that was

a regiment of those students who did not live in the dormitory day students complete with company commander who was a day student my company commander was rucker you know him he's the he's still active around there he was head of the
What is it, the guy who does all this landscaping and that sort of thing?
Environmental, urban and environmental planning.
Yeah.
Oh, he's in a magazine here just the other day.
Rucker, he's a company commander.
Heart of Culture, I guess he is.
Oh, okay.
Yeah.
He was a professor there for a year.
He just recently retired, and now he's
He still got a job doing something around there.
My roommate was a company commander, a wrecker, Bill Rector.
He lives in Kern now.
But I wasn't out as second lieutenant the senior year.
So we farmed and drilled it.
Everything except we didn't live in the area.
Drilled right along with them on burial day.
And this was C Company, I forget.
I guess I can look it up in the yearbook.
How many were in the company?
As I recall, about 150.
There were four or five companies in the battalion, and there were three battalions.
Did you plan the ban?
Not any of them.
I worked my tail off.
Oh, you didn't have time to plan the ban?
I'm not sure I could play well enough snare drum.
I don't know.
I never did try out because it was impossible because I couldn't.
Because I worked before.
Classes, after classes, and on weekends.
What kind of student were you?
About an average.
Tell me about hazing.
Well, we even got hazed even though he was a day student.
Sure.
And even though I was a sophomore,
I still wore the white strike, which we wore then as a freshman.
See, I was a freshman at A&M, even though I was classified as a sophomore academically.
Oh, yeah.
Got those great big things wrapped with tape, heavy, and heat to pick them up.
It'd particularly get you if you went up in a hall, see?
And you shouldn't be up there.
Some of those stuff would probably get you if you
And even down there on the dairy farm, the seniors and the upperclassmen, nobody ever got hurt, which you'd be sure would get bruised.
What was the purpose of hazing, do you think?
Well, of course, stupidity.
Sadistic.
Child.
childlike behavior.
A custom, see, and then they have to maintain the custom.
And finally, the freshman comes up to class and he says, this is the way I was treated.
Do you think there's any beneficial aspect to hazing?
There is, but I don't think it's
justified by the result.
See, they have hazing at West Point.
I spent four years there as an instructor, not as a student.
It's not called hazing.
They call it custom there.
Of course, they don't beat them.
You can't touch another cadet at West Point.

But sometimes it would be much better if you did touch them because one of the things they do there is holding up the wall, for example, where you squat and you stay there and finally you just collapse.
It would be better, like they did at A&M, is to have you bend over and take a few licks and go on to something else.
Of course, there's other kind of hate in A&M.
But speaking of A&M, I read an article in Texas Monthly, I guess it was,
about A&M, and they said this is a custom that had been going on for years.
I didn't recognize any of those things when we were there, yet they say that's a long-standing custom of all these people.
I thought that was a pathetic article.
This is the one about two or three months ago?
Yeah.
It's supposed to have been written by a nagging.

But anyway, the beneficial part of hazing only is this, that if you have an environment, a controlled environment, and it's difficult, and those who are tested and pass the test, major up to the test, one would conclude that they are better men having experienced this and now.
But the bad part, the negative part of that, how many really outstanding people who just say,
To hell with that.
I'm not going to put up with this.
Life's too short.
That might have been the best student that you're going to have here.
So you think that Hazen might have kept some good students away?
Well, probably so.
But me, I was proud of it, see, once again.
As I go through this, you'll probably say, well, you were quite naive, perhaps I was.
But to me, I didn't mind it.
And I could do anything anybody else could do, and nobody was going to beat me down or break my will of spirit.
Even used to that baseball games would make you eat tobacco, not chew it, you know, but put it in there and drink, take some water.
Of course, that makes you deathly ill and can kill you, of course.
Very serious, the same as others.
like paternities do with all this drinking where an individual actually can't even drink a fifth of liquor or something like that.
The system can't tolerate that.
So hazing, there may be some aspects, like at the military academy, that's controlled.
But the thing about it, your upperclassmen, their kids also.
Seniors doesn't mean that they're just so mature they're going to be sure.
And you get some sadistic people.
the kind that would kick and torment an animal, you know, kill things.
Well, you let that kind of guy under the... You give him power.
Yeah, you get him, and you go to really have something.
And that's the reason why hazing, there's no place for hazing anywhere, at A&M or at the military academy.
Mental and physical hazing.
That's right.
Now, at the military academy, it's really tough, the way they handle their pleas.
But it's more of an endurance than it is a physical abuse.
Let's say you can't touch another cadet.
Do you think it's tougher?
Do you think that the mental hazing there was tougher at West Point than it is at A&M, the physical hazing?
I mean, which one is tougher to survive?
Well, probably the military academy.
The only thing I can compare to the military camp is that I was never a cadet.
But I was in the tactical department.
I worked with the cadets every day and every night.
But that environment is so different.
See, lights go out at a certain time.
And if you're found in the train studying, you're given demerits for it.
If you get so many demerits, you've got to go out and walk them off
So there is a very rigid control environment.
I'd even go this far to say it's probably the closest to a perfect environment.
I'm not talking about hating, hating outside, but you will find.
What do you mean perfect?
Well, there's no lying, cheating, or stealing.
And you don't tolerate anybody that does.
You're forced to go to chapel whether you want to.
Everything is controlled.
You're fed a rounded meal, although in hazing, they don't let their police eat square meals.
But morally, everything about it is.
And it misleads some cadets, particularly if they come there when they're naive.
From a sheltered home, they go through that.
They get the rudest wagon you've ever seen whenever they get out in the real world and find out that the people you were dealing with were lie, cheat, and steal.
It's a shock to them.
That's what I mean.
For four years there, without a controlled environment.
And I thoroughly enjoyed that.
It's an inspiration.
Now let's get back to the Corps.
What were the things that you liked about the Corps?
Well, of course, every ag is a spirit.
Yeah.
You don't have to be there very long at all.
You know that you've got a lot of friends and through life.
Even though you don't know them.
I go around now, I might be taking my car to the garage to have it serviced.
And I had an old time the other day that said, I see you've got an ag in what class, you know.
And you go up.
Felix Daly, who has a dealership here in tires and other things.
He's a .
So I go there to buy tires.
I never knew him before, but I knew he was.
And not only does he give you a good deal, but the service is great.
And so it's not.
This, of course, is a little bit monetary benefit
But it's just the spirit.
And it goes on and on.
It's football games.
Of course, this is about the old stadium or the earlier stadium.
If you go there, you can just feel it.
So I'd say the spirit in the academic program
Were there any things about the Corps that you disliked?
No.
I didn't particularly dislike the hazing, although I'm against hazing.
What way do you think that the Corps helped you in your career?
a great deal for the training.
Because I really thought a lot of our tactical losses we had there, the camp we had, the bullets, and the parades, and the bands.
At that time, it was the nearest thing to West Point.
And they prided themselves.
And most of our tactical officers were West Point graduates.
Many of them died in World War II in the Philippines.
They also just happened to rotate.
They left there just about time to go to the Philippines and get killed or captured.
So the training was very helpful in your career.
Anything else?
If you're... See, I'm...
I'm perceiving it, or really experiencing it, as an individual who had an objective to become a professional officer.
So I would get more out of the Corps than an individual who says, well, I enjoy all of this.
In fact, right around the corner up here is Dennis Aggie.
And boy, he was a high ranking.
was a lieutenant colonel.
He commanded a battalion.
But he loved all of this, yet his profession, and what he always wanted to be, was a dentist.
So maybe it's more than just because I was interested in that type of thing, because, and he goes back, he even went to, we played Michigan.
They went up there to Michigan for that game.
Of course, he wished he'd stayed at home when they got 40 to,
two on it or something, or three, something like that.
And so I, besides the spirit and the academic, and of course I didn't miss the lack of recreation because I was working on it.
Sure, absolutely.
In those days, of course, they were out in the boondocks, you know.
Do you think there was anything about being in the Corps that might not have helped you, that might have hindered your career or your advancement?
Do you think that the Corps had any impact on you becoming a general officer, becoming a leader?
Oh, I'm sure it did.
What was it?
It was a training.
Because, see, ROTC is training leaders.
Training young men to be leaders.
And so everything you do in a Corps of Cadets, besides the instructions you get,
It's toward that end.
That's where you have cadet officers, student officers, and right on from a corporal sergeant.
So you give them that leadership training.
Yeah, small.
We do the same thing, officer academy school, same thing to military academy.
Now, were there professional soldiers at A&M that had a particular impact on you or an influence?
You said the training was tops.
And who were those West Point men that had that?
Well, one of them was Moses, Captain Moses.
Yeah, I've heard of him.
Fair enough.
How did he influence you?
Well, once again, he sort of epitomized the spittin' pollies.
They were wrecked and everything he did.
military bearing, you know.
And you just say that he looks and acts like what I would consider to be a military officer.
And too, in those days, you know, they didn't have any colonels, no generals, you know.
In fact, when I later on, when we get to it, when I went to Fort San Houston, I had to graduate.
At that time, the entire army was only 130,000.
We have more officers now than then.
He was a peacemaker.
And so being a captain, we did have a major, major then, I've forgotten his name.
One, though, was Moore, who was a later general officer who was captured in the Philippines.
Moore?
Moore, yes.
I think he was a graduate also of A&M.
But the one that I really enjoyed, I wouldn't select him as a role model, but...
He was named Orr, O-R-R.
He was an East Texas guy.
He got his commission in World War I, so he wasn't a west corner.
He gave us a lot of enjoyment, just the way he talked and the way he acted, although he was very military and a very good solid individual.
He wasn't a comic or anything like that.
But I guess all those would be Moore.
Moses particularly, I would say, because he was younger and worked more closely with us.
Moore, I think, was .
But he wasn't a commandant.
Because we had a civilian commandant, a very big, fat guy that used to be able to suck in his gut and his pants would drop off.
He had great thinking.
Then Moore later on became a commandant.
That's right.
And I forget that, now that was a comic when he used to drop his pants and have Yale practice.
Did all the other things.
So he'd get up there and suck in his gut, down his pants.
Now, if we compared Second Lieutenant's products from
A&M and West Point and other ROTC schools, what would you say about the quality of those brand new second lieutenants?
You mean today?
No, back then.
Back then?
Yeah.
Back in the 30s.
Well, of course, it's difficult to compare them with West Point because of the amount of

military training, I'm talking about then, that they have as compared to the amount of, because they have military training not only during the year like we have at A&M, you know, with three classes a week or two classes a week, but each summer they're involved in living a military life, see the camp and so forth.
So when they graduate, then when they graduate, they have a
considerably more experienced.
Well, that would have put A&M superior to the other ROTC programs, except when you consider the Citadel, VMI, and API.
No, the school up in Massachusetts.
But BMI and the Citadel, they are very similar to West Point in that they devote much more time.
But A&M in those days would, I'd say, be right up there.
Of course, I'm biased.
I'd put A&M next to the military academy.
But those other schools are very fine.
From a military standpoint.
But in general, from military training, you put West Point on number one tops.
Yeah.
Because they're limited 24 hours a day.
Yeah.
OK. See, every class.
Of course, it's impossible now.
You're not comparing.
You can't compare the Corps cadets.
At A&M now, of course, I don't know how they operate now with West Point.
Because I say, there is 24 hours a day.
Even their academic is military controlled discipline type thing, even though they have professors, of course, that are highly qualified.
And they have permanent professors, which means that they no longer, they
won't actually do anything like that.
Most of them, of course, have PhDs in their particular specialty.
But now it's different.
In many cases, a graduate of ROTC now can run out of school now.
We're talking about right after graduation.
Because of the school system that you graduate from A&M,
Then you go to, well, first you go to, their summer camp now is much different than the summer camp we had.
It was more intense.
So they got training very similar.
Now I'm going to appear to contradict myself.
People think of West Point as being just a military.
But they spend so much of their time on academics, when you add it all up together now, there isn't a great deal of difference.
Both of them intend to get their education after they graduate.
In other words, you have basic training as a lieutenant, and you're qualified then.
But you really got to specialize.
It didn't fare.
And I know that, but we did at West Point.
These kids graduated, and we sent them to Korea while I was up there.
And I went to Korea and interviewed all of these youngsters.
And it wasn't fair to put them out and throw them right into combat, because they
had intended for them to go to school, to Benning, to engineer school, wherever it is, and really develop the skill and the knowledge that you'd expect of a second lieutenant.
And they had a heavy caliber.
It wasn't because of lack of knowledge that they had caliber, indirectly it was.
It's because they were going to prove that they were graduating military academy as second lieutenant.
And so they were out leading when they shouldn't be out there.
Yeah, right.
They were sacrificed.
They had heavy cases.
Let's talk about your academic career at A&M.
You were in dairy husbandry.
Did you like the curriculum?
Did you enjoy the courses?
I had no idea.
When I graduated from high school that I'd be involved in things like that.
But, yeah, I enjoyed it.
And see, in dairy husbandry, you've got production and manufacturing.
And I was in the manufacturing part.
And so I was doing what, you know, in the creamer there.
Sure.
That was helping you.
And of course, you know, your basic course, you take chemistry and biology and English and history, you know, a whole range of things.
So it didn't just down to the old dairy farm.
Sure.
Were there professors there that had a particular influence on you?
Right.
Jefferson did.
He took the time, he interviewed, talked to us.
In fact, he wanted to keep up with each student, so he had a plan where he called Jen every once in a while.
They'd just say, well, how you doing?
Are you enjoying your work?
And he'd come in business there in Greenwood.
Brilliant individual.
He's from the Middle West, I think.
Minnesota, I think, is where he came from.
When you finished your education, did you ever give any thought to going into dairy husbandry, or did you want to go right into the military?
Well, if I hadn't gone to the military, yeah.
So that was your second choice then?
Yeah.
In fact, I even thought at one time that I might probably become a veterinarian.
because I hadn't taken the courses.
Of course, I had to go take quite a few more, but it wouldn't have been much difficult before that.
In fact, I had planned, if I had not gotten my regular commission in World War II, I probably would have gone back to A&M to become a veterinarian.
I would like very much to stay in Terry Hudson, particularly the manufacturing part of it.
And I offered a job after I graduated in San Antonio.
In fact, I went for an interview.
But then I had applied for Thomason Act.
I don't know if you ever heard of Thomason Act.
Sure have.
The Army was understaffed of officers.
And West Point wasn't producing sufficient.
So they had a shortage of officers, acute shortage.
So this representative named Thomason had a bill passed that would call into service 1,000 officers, ROTC graduates, for one year competitive tour of duty, which out of that
50 would be selected for a regular commission.
So just when I was being interviewed, my name was approved to attend or to go for a year's active duty.
Of course, that's what I wanted.
So I went to Fort Sam Houston in the second division.
And how long did you stay at Fort Sam?
One year.
And tell me about the training.
This is 1938.
Tell me about the training.
Well, I would consider now on-the-job training.
I had a company commander named Dansby, and so he took me under his wing to teach me about really how to be a company commander, being a company officer.
And I was the only other officer they had.
Unfortunately, I had Sergeant Bieber, a German immigrant that had been in the army.
He got into the army when he was real young, in the US Army.
And he got interested in me.
So he taught me.
Now we send them to service school to go through all of this.
This was only job training.
And that's what the purpose of the year.
And then later on, we had organized formal school training.
So obviously, I became the mess officer, the supply officer, the training officer, administrative officer, and any other odd job.
Like we had the inventory of the and the commissary.
So that only happened once a month.
We also had to perform as officers of the day.
And the other was officer of the guard, officer of the guard.
He went down to the stockade, you know, and inspected the prisoners out working.
So it was a full-time job.
Now, each of the sergeants teaches, the supply sergeant would teach you all about supply and the book and so forth.
Same thing with the mess officer.
One anecdote that I think is, that I would know better today, of course, but being young and want to impress my company commander.
And knowing your first day of duty, the importance to make a faithful impression.
So I had my boots all shined, spurs, and I was ready.
So I went walking in the C Company, 9th Infantry.
The medical people are taking all that over now.
And so I walked in fresh out of A&M as a second lieutenant.
And when I walked in, I would have yelled, .
Boy, I came to attention.
Used to responding.
And then when I discovered that he was calling attention for me, the second lieutenant walked in.
And he was the orderly.
Orly was outside the company commandant's door.
So then when I felt that's what had happened and realized it, I started to step off.
And my spurs, they will hang together.
They hook together.
I tried getting those unhooked.
Of course, I was embarrassed.
And you could see that Orly, looking at the tension, but he's kind of smirk on his face like, oh, it's this lieutenant.
So I walked in, and Captain Danley saluted Lieutenant Andrews and reported the duty.
He said, oh, I'm glad to see you.
I'm looking forward to it.
I've got all this work I've got to get done.
And by the way, he says, we're getting ready to have a parade.
And I want you to take the company, because I'm busy here.
I said, yes, sir.
He said, well, you better move on out, because they're getting ready.
And so Sergeant Beaver came up to me, and he said,
I said, Lieutenant, do you know anything about mass formation?
No, never heard of it.
He said, well, this is a test division for the new triangular organization, and we're drilling today on mass formation.
That's where the parade was.
I said, no, I know all about right by squad, squad to right, and you know all of that stuff, which we'd been doing at A&M and everywhere else in the Army except for St. Lucie.
He said, well, I'll tell you what I'll do, Lieutenant.
Instead of, you know, when you follow them, you just post and the sergeant goes around the back.
He said, I'll stay right behind you.
And he said, I'll give you every command that you need to do.
And I said, okay.
Knowing what I know now, rather than, you know, gosh, you could have a,
tragedy out there, you know, here you've got people lined up.
It's an entire division parade, you know, and I'm taking up the company, supposed to be the final of the battalion.
But I didn't.
I said, yeah, okay, Sergeant, thank you very much.
So we went out and he said, come to Mass Right.
Well, I said, come to Mass Right.
You know, they all reacted.
And he carried me around and gave me, of course, all I had to do was know, I knew all about grieving, you know, what to do and all that stuff.
And we carried it all the way around.
passed the review and came on back to the company and dismissed him.
And the old sergeant said, Lieutenant, you did real well.
And I said, thank you, boy, I'm really indebted to you.
And the old Danvy committed me.
He said, Sergeant Beaver tells me you did a good job.
That was great.
And I never did tell him that I didn't know anything about that.
I don't know.
He may not realize, I don't know, but I'd never send a lieutenant out like that.
Boy, you can really mess up here and embarrass me.
You want to go eat now?
Sure, I can go eat.
OK, we were talking about life at Fort Sam Houston.
Yeah.
After your year was over there, of course, it was questionable if you were going to give a regular, if you would receive a regular Army commission.
Is that not right?
And tell me how that transpired, how you received it.
Well, as I said, the second part of the year, I had to get on the job training, which the sergeants taught us a lot, which you have to rely very heavily, all through the military on the sergeants.
Then we had organized classes where we went to school and stayed.
Those were just map reading, something such as that, weapon training.
And then at the end, we were given a test.
And at Fort Sam Houston, we had about 20 competing.
And only one got a regular commission, which I wasn't that one.
But he was an Aggie, and it was a name comes to mind is Cersei Bracewell, but I don't think that was the one.
He was an artilleryman, I remember.
So then after the year was over, of course, we had to wait to see whether or not
And that didn't receive work.
We found out later on it only once.
So I had a month's leave.
So I hitchhiked by air.
People laugh when I say that, because how do you hitchhike by air?
But went out to the military field to go to operations and ask for their plane going to the west coast.
Finally, I got a ride out to the West Coast.
San Francisco, went to the San Francisco World's Fair, which was one of the great attractions.
Sally ran in the news range.
And then hitchhiked, went out to one of the local fields, and hitchhiked back to Dallas.
And this would be a great historical occurrence.
It was a nonstop flight in a bomber from California to Dallas.
